{"id": 125576, "acmi_id": "", "title": "Frog Detective 1: The Haunted Island", "title_zh_hans": "", "title_pa": "", "title_hi": "", "title_annotation": "", "title_annotation_zh_hans": "", "title_annotation_pa": "", "title_annotation_hi": "", "slug": "frog-detective-1-the-haunted-island", "creator_credit": "Worm Club", "credit_line": "", "credit_line_zh_hans": "", "credit_line_pa": "", "credit_line_hi": "", "headline_credit": "Melbourne, Victoria, Australia, 2018", "video_links": [], "record_type": "group", "type": "Film", "is_on_display": false, "last_on_display_place": "ACMI", "last_on_display_date": "2027-07-30", "is_context_indigenous": false, "material_description": "", "unpublished": false, "external": false, "first_production_date": "2018-01-01T11:00:00+11:00", "commissioned": false, "public_domain": false, "external_references": [], "brief_description": "<p>In Frog Detective 1: The Haunted Island, the stereotype of a hard-boiled detective becomes a friendly frog investigating a ghostly noise. Developed by Grace Bruxner while she was still studying game design, this first game in the Frog Detective trilogy turns detective fiction into a silly, kind-hearted adventure.<br />\nIt borrows from screen mysteries like Agatha Christie’s Poirot (1989), using familiar music, camera angles and episodic structure. But the mystery is deliberately low-stakes, and the detective is polite, enthusiastic and apologetic when suspicious. Through comic dialogue and absurd interviews, Bruxner finds humour in making noir softer, stranger and much more charming.</p>", "constellations_primary": [], "constellations_other": [{"id": 383, "name": "Animal hijinks", "description": "As long as stories have been told on screen, audiences have loved films, TV shows, memes and videogames about animals being naughty. This constellation shares some key examples of animal comedy throughout the ages."}], "recommendations": [], "creator_credit_for_label": "<p>Worm Club</p>", "creator_credit_for_labe